column10: I was cycling northbound on Meade Street when a driver approaching from the Route 50 offramp initially ignored a stop sign and nearly hit me.
Driver didnt see me.  I yelled he stopped last sec

I fell (I do not fall easily on that bike - about once every 10 years or so and usually involving a vehicle).  Other cyclists were slipping as well.; sidewalk,(very,used,by,cyclists,on,approach,to,Key,bridge),had,several,inches,of,mud/tree,debris.,

I was crossing from NW to SW corner, car came from Wilson, made a fast left from Quinn to Scott, cutting the corner. I saw it coming. I sped up, felt the car pass inches from me, yelled in shock.  The car stopped 50+ ft later, no brakes before then

I was hit by a car running left on a green light unto Lee Hwy that did not yield as I was crossing in the crosswalk during the walk signal. The only reason I was nit injured is because the vehicle swiped my large crossbody bag instead of my leg. ssbody

column10: Cars turning right onto N. Lynn street won't always stop when runners/bicyclist have the green light at the crosswalk.  It is an extremely unnerving crosswalk to go over every weekday during rush hour.
Car driver turning from southbound Ft Myers Dr/Key Br to the GW Pkwy westbound ramp failed to yield to peds and cyclists in the crosswalk/MUP.
Driver was not paying attention and almost collided with cyclist (me)
I was cycling southbound through the crosswalk of the famed Intersection of Doom. Despite having the walk signal, I was nearly hit by two drivers turning right and failing to yield.
Cars ignore the No right turn sign and make a right on to Key Bridge at speed.

cars proceed even though pedestrians and cyclists have walking signal.  two lanes of traffic turning left caused near miss because cars eager to get light.  there should be more of a delay before the cars can proceed

Drivers have light to turn right and don't realize bikes are coming downhill at high speed and have a walk signal. It's hard on the bike to either have to stop or assert yourself to make the cars stop.

Cars going EB on Langston Blvd go downhill, often too fast, and tend to run the red light at Langston Blvd and N Nash Stat the bottom of the hill. On this particular day, I was crossing Langston Blvd on N Nash St and once I got the green light, noticed a car traveling EB on Langston Blvd that did not seem like they were going to stop for their red light, which had been red for several seconds. I waited and watched them run through the red light, and proceeded once they cleared the intersection.
column21: Additional signage or slower speed limit on EB Langston Blvd from N Quinn St to N Nash St could alert drivers to the stoplight that is coming up

column10: Langston/ N Quinn intersection is a downhill section of the Curtis Trail.  Cyclists do not need to stop.  Vehicles cannot see cyclists due to the wall blocking the view until they are in the crosswalk.  Near misses occur here daily.  We live at the corner and hear cyclist breaks, honks, yelling, emergency vehicles responding.
